The exact year of founding is unknown. According to shrine tradition, before a dedicated sanctuary existed, {{ill|Konohanasakuya-hime|ja|木花開耶姫命|1=Konohanasakuya-hime|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} was enshrined on a local wild cherry tree, hence the name “Sakurabana Daimyōjin.” In the 4th year of {{ill|Chōtoku (era)|ja|長徳 (日本)|lt=Chōtoku|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (998), {{ill|Sugawara no Sukemasa|ja|菅原輔正|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} is said to have invited the spirit of {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} to this site, creating the dual dedication to Yukisugi Tenmangū.  
Ashizumi Jinja is considered a ronsha (candidate shrine) for one of the ancient {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. It served as the sōsha (general shrine) of the Zenzumigō region and later became a former {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.  
Imazu-chō Hirokawa is regarded as within the area of the “Zenzumi-gō” mentioned in “Wamyō Ruijushō.” The name “Zenzumi” may originally have been “Ashizumi” (written as 葦積), matching the pronunciation “Ashi-tsumi” of the shrine’s name—though from a more archaic linguistic perspective, “Ashizumi” may have roots in “Azumi” (安曇), suggesting a link with the Azumi clan.<ref>京都滋賀古代地名を歩く 著者: 吉田金彦 出版社: 京都新聞社 発売日: 1987</ref>
== Festivals ==
=== Rituals ===
* The '''annual festival''' (festival) is held on [[April 25]]<ref name=reisai>Only religious rites (saigi) are performed on this day.</ref>.
* The '''Hirokawa Festival''' takes place on April 29 ({{ill|Shōwa Day|ja|昭和の日|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}), featuring a parade where a {{ill|Mikoshi|ja|御輿|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} is carried through the local community.
=== Shrine Priest Family ===
The Taya family has historically held the hereditary priesthood for this shrine.
== Subsidiary Shrines ==
* '''Inari Jinja'''  
* '''Hakusan Jinja''' — Merged from two separate Hakusan shrines formerly in Kita-Umimi and Minami-Umimi.
